  <!-- R-290 CALLOUT -->
  <section class="r290-section">
    <div class="container r290-inner">
      <div class="r290-icon">⚠️</div>
      <div class="r290-body">
        <h2>R-290 Propane Refrigerant — Know Before You Call</h2>
        <p>True Refrigeration has transitioned current-production THAC back bar coolers and select commercial models to R-290 propane refrigerant. R-290 is a hydrocarbon refrigerant with near-zero global warming potential — significantly more environmentally friendly than R-404A or R-134a. However, it requires EPA 608 certification with specific hydrocarbon refrigerant training, and technicians must use approved equipment designed for flammable refrigerants.</p>
        <p>The practical implication: if your True back bar cooler or display unit was manufactured after approximately 2019 and the model number ends in "HC," it likely contains R-290. <strong>Never allow an uncertified technician to work on R-290 equipment.</strong> Propane refrigerant handled improperly in an enclosed bar or kitchen space is a fire and explosion hazard. We are fully certified and equipped for R-290 service throughout SoCal.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
  <section class="repairs-section container">
    <h2>Recent True Refrigeration Service Calls</h2>
    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"T-49 reach-in — warm, compressor running, Hollywood restaurant"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Hollywood, Los Angeles</p>
        <p>Called Friday afternoon — True T-49 running at 52°F, compressor audible, dinner service in 3 hours. Classic grease-kitchen pattern: evaporator fans completely coated with cooking grease, airflow reduced to near zero. Cleaned both evaporator fan assemblies, confirmed defrost system operational. Unit at 38°F within 90 minutes — well before service. Also found the door gasket on the right door showing wear at the bottom left corner; replaced with OEM True gasket on the same visit. Restaurant didn't lose inventory.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>Evaporator fan cleaning in restaurant reach-ins: every 6 months minimum. Grease-heavy kitchens: quarterly.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"GDM-49 glass door fogging, convenience store South LA"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 South Los Angeles</p>
        <p>GDM-49 glass door merchandiser, both doors fogging constantly — customer complaints about not being able to see product. Door heater wire failure on both doors (common in high-humidity environments, both wires often fail within months of each other). Replaced the door heater wire assembly on both doors with OEM True parts. While there, inspected the door gaskets — right door lower gasket had a 3-inch separation. Replaced. Total visit: 2.5 hours. Customer was previously having a refrigeration company come out monthly to "wipe down the doors" without diagnosing the root cause.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>GDM door fogging is almost always a heater wire failure. "Wiping" the glass treats the symptom.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"TSSU-48 prep table — pan rail at 48°F, lunch service, Mid-City"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 Mid-City Los Angeles</p>
        <p>QSR kitchen, TSSU-48 sandwich prep showing 48°F in pan rail at 10am — above the 41°F food safety threshold. LA County health inspector due that afternoon. Condenser coil completely loaded with kitchen dust and grease — the unit simply couldn't dissipate heat fast enough to maintain the pan rail temperature, especially with the lid open during service. Cleaned the condenser, confirmed 38°F in cabinet and 40°F in pan rail within 30 minutes. Restaurant passed inspection. Sent a maintenance reminder for 3-month cleaning intervals.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>TSSU prep tables: 41°F food safety requirement. Dirty condenser + summer heat = health code violation risk.</em></p>
      </div>
      <div class="repair-card">
        <h3>"THAC-48 back bar — not cooling, WeHo cocktail bar"</h3>
        <p class="repair-loc">📍 West Hollywood</p>
        <p>THAC-48 back bar cooler, 2021 model with R-290 propane refrigerant. Unit not cooling, compressor not starting. Confirmed R-290 system (model number suffix "HC"). Tested start relay and capacitor — start capacitor failed. Replaced with OEM True R-290 compatible capacitor, confirmed compressor start and proper operating pressures under R-290 parameters. Bar had called two other companies who declined the job when they saw the R-290 designation. R-290 work is straightforward for certified technicians — the hesitation is a certification and equipment issue, not a difficulty issue.</p>
        <p class="repair-note"><em>R-290 True units: two other companies declined. Certification is the barrier, not the complexity.</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MAINTENANCE BLOCK -->
  <section class="maint-section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>True Refrigeration Maintenance — SoCal Commercial Schedule</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Standard maintenance intervals assume normal environments. SoCal restaurant, bar, and convenience store environments are not normal — high ambient heat, grease, and humidity require shorter intervals.</p>
      <div class="maint-grid">
        <div class="maint-card">
          <div class="maint-interval">Monthly</div>
          <ul class="maint-tasks">
            <li>Condenser coil inspection &amp; cleaning (bar undercounters)</li>
            <li>Door gasket inspection — check for tears, separation, loss of seal</li>
            <li>Temperature verification — confirm holding temperature against food safety requirements</li>
            <li>Interior cleaning and sanitization</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="maint-card">
          <div class="maint-interval">Quarterly</div>
